args: This guy's still wet behind the ears!\nHow the hell is he beating us?!
Welcome home, Alberius. It seems you\nrepelled the imperials alone yet again.
I just took the most appropriate steps to\nwin. But enough on thatâ€”I have a favor\nI need to ask you.
Speak, and let us see if I will grant it.
I want to leave the allied forces\nin your command for a while.
Yes. I make for the Faerie Kingdom.

You recall how I fought the Other recently?
The power I saw on display that day was
overwhelming. I cannot defeat him as I
am now.
And so your mind turns to the sorcery the\nfaerie emissary spoke of. But as you said,\nwe have no basis for believing them.

What happened to the power of the bonds
you forged fighting at the side of others?
Would you discard them in favor of some
baseless promise?
I will face down the Other by myself;\nif there is something I can do to increase\nmy chance of victory, I must seize it.
Then you lack faith in your companions.
You misunderstand. My fighting alone\nis simply the best chance for victory.
Do not make so close a companion of your\nhubris, Alberius. It does not watch your\nback as I do!
Come at me, Alberius, that I might\nstamp this arrogance out of you!
If you think to fight the Other alone,\nI would first put you to the test!
...All right. But I don't want to hear\nany complaints when I beat you!
THIS is your best? If this is all you have\nto offer, you ought to spend time reflecting\non the foolishness of fighting alone!
I am the victor. Are you convinced now?
Why do you not put your faith in us?\nAre you trying to suggest that we\nare no longer your comrades?
It is BECAUSE I have faith in my comrades\nthat I will learn the faerie's secret rite.
I will defeat the Otherâ€”alone.\nIf what the faeries claim is true,\ntheir magic will make it possible.
They claimed it is a power no ordinary\nperson can handle; that only one of your\ncaliber could successfully seal the Other.
Supposing that this rite actually CAN\ndefeat the Other, thenâ€”in theoryâ€”\nyou could best the creature alone.
But theory does not bear the weight of\npracticality, and I cannot assent to you\nfighting by yourself on such a basis.

The Other's power is immenseâ€”far
beyond anything that could be surmounted
with sheer numbers. I'd rather not have us
make unnecessary sacrifices.
You may not intend your words to carry\nthis meaning, but they sound as though\nyou consider us but a hindrance.
That's not what I'm trying to say.\nAll of you have a roleâ€”a critical oneâ€”\nthat I cannot hope to manage myself.
I can defeat the Other by myself,\nbut I cannot do what comes next:\nThe building of a peaceful world.
After I'm gone, I wish to leave the world\nin everyone's capable hands.
Apparently, using the rite means one will\nsuffer a pain equal to that of death itselfâ€”\na pain that continues without end.

Obviously I'm not planning on dying any
time soonâ€”so when I say ï¼‚when I'm
gone,ï¼‚ I don't mean right away.
But I'm talking about things beyond that.
Still, this is a watershed moment,\none when we determine if the world\nI seek and hope for can be realized!
That part of you is ever unchanging;\nit has been so since first we met.
You have not. However, you clearly\nwill not hear what I have to say.
Ha ha ha! Perhaps you're right, at that.\nRegardless, Windwyrm, I would ask you\nto abide my selfishness for a little longer.
I suppose I've no choice in the matter.\nNow go, before others can question you.
That day, Alberius set out on a journey\nto the Faerie Kingdom.
The allied forces were shaken by the sudden\ndeparture of their hero, but structure was\nmaintained thanks to Midgardsormr.
Thus did three months pass, absent the hero.
